{"id": "1206.0976", "review": {"conference": "arxiv", "VERSION": "v1", "DATE_OF_SUBMISSION": "5-Jun-2012", "title": "Loopy Belief Propagation in Bayesian Networks : origin and possibilistic perspectives", "abstract": "in this paper we present a map of the work performed on two inference algorithms : the kernel's error avoidance ( bp ) algorithm applied to bayesian networks without observations ( i. e. polytree ) and the loopy selection optimization ( lbp ) algorithm ( inspired from the bp ) which is applied to networks containing undirected numbers. it is known in the bp algorithm, applied the conditional networks with loops, gives incorrect numerical results i. e. incorrect posterior probabilities. murphy and al. [ 7 ] find that the lbp algorithm converges on several segments and when this occurs, lbp gives a good approximation of those exact posterior probabilities. however this algorithm presents an altered behaviour though it is applied between qmr ( quick medical reference ) network [ 18 ]. this phenomenon prevents the lbp algorithm from converging towards a good approximate of posterior probabilities. we believe that the translation of the shannon computation problem from the probabilistic framework, the possibilistic setting possibly allow performance improvement of lbp algorithm. to hope that an adaptation of this algorithm to a possibilistic causal network will show an improvement into the convergence of lbp.", "histories": [["v1", "Tue, 5 Jun 2012 16:14:16 GMT  (153kb)", "http://arxiv.org/abs/1206.0976v1", "The International Conference on Computing &amp; e-Systems - 2007"]], "COMMENTS": "The International Conference on Computing &amp; e-Systems - 2007", "reviews": [], "SUBJECTS": "cs.AI cs.IR", "authors": ["amen ajroud", "mohamed nazih omri", "habib youssef", "salem benferhat"], "accepted": false, "id": "1206.0976"}, "pdf": {"name": "1206.0976.pdf", "metadata": {"source": "CRF", "title": null, "authors": [], "emails": ["@E"], "sections": [{"heading": null,